  <title>  The <insect>Bee</insect>
</title>
<author>By Emily Dickinson</author>
<poem>
  <line n="1"> Like <vehicle>trains</vehicle> of  <vehicle>cars</vehicle> on tracks of plush</line>
<line n="2">I hear the level <insect>bee:</insect></line>
<line n="3">A jar across the flowers goes,</line>
<line n="4">Their velvet masonry</line>

<line n="5">Withstands until the sweet assault</line>
<line n="6">Their chivalry consumes,</line>
<line n="7">While he, victorious, tilts away</line>
<line n="8">To vanquish other blooms.</line>

<line n="9">His feet are shod with gauze,</line>
<line n="10">His helmet is of gold;</line>
<line n="11">His breast, a single onyx</line>
<line n="12">With chrysoprase, inlaid.</line>

<line n="13">His labor is a chant,</line>
<line n="14">His idleness a tune;</line>
<line n="15">Oh, for a <insect>beeâ€™s</insect> experience </line>
<line n="16">Of clovers and of noon!</line>
</poem>
